# KUKA Fieldbus

When working on I/O, fieldbus mapping, or PLC-robot integration:

## Supported Fieldbuses

| Bus | Typical Role | KUKA Option |
|-----|--------------|-------------|
| **Profinet** | PLC ↔ KR C4/C5 in European / Siemens-centric plants | KUKA.Profinet M/S |
| **EtherNet/IP** | PLC ↔ KR C4/C5 in North American / Rockwell plants | KUKA.EthernetIP M/S |
| **EtherCAT** | High-deterministic external axes and drives | Native to KR C4/C5 KSS |
| **DeviceNet** | Legacy | KUKA.DeviceNet |
| **Profibus** | Legacy European | KUKA.Profibus |

## Architectural Patterns

### PLC-Master / Robot-Slave (most common for work-cell integration)

- PLC owns cell orchestration; robot receives program-number / start signals and reports state.
- Use **KUKA.PLC mxAutomation** when the PLC needs to command motion (palletizing, multi-path) via function blocks — robot runs a dedicated mxAutomation application and exposes motion FBs over the fieldbus.
- For pure trigger/ack (program select + start), plain Profinet/EtherNet-IP I/O is sufficient.

### Robot-Master / PLC-Slave

- Less common; used when the robot sequences the cell.
- Robot reads sensors and commands auxiliary devices via fieldbus outputs.

### External Control (real-time)

- **RSI (RobotSensorInterface)** — real-time path correction from sensors (12 ms cycle). Used for seam tracking, force control, visual servoing. Requires RSI option.
- **EKI XML** — soft-real-time XML over TCP for messaging. Used for loose-coupled data exchange with non-PLC systems.

## I/O Configuration

- I/O is configured in **WorkVisual**, not in program code. Program code references **aliases** declared in `$config.dat` via `SIGNAL name $IN[n] TO $IN[m]` or `SIGNAL name $OUT[k]`.
- Never hardcode `$IN[17]`; always alias: `SIGNAL part_present $IN[17]`.
- Input debounce and output pulse logic in dedicated subprograms, not scattered.

## Handshake Patterns

Prefer explicit handshakes over blind waits. Template pattern:

```krl
; Request pattern: set request, wait for ack, clear request, wait for ack clear
$OUT[req_bit] = TRUE
WAIT FOR $IN[ack_bit] == TRUE
$OUT[req_bit] = FALSE
WAIT FOR $IN[ack_bit] == FALSE
```

Every `WAIT FOR` must have a timeout via `INTERRUPT` or `WAIT SEC <t>` fallback — never unbounded.

